✅ Final note – exceptional alert(1) for fully hardened app
If the application has:

CSP: default-src 'self'; script-src 'nonce-...' (no unsafe-inline, no unsafe-eval)

Sanitizer: removes all HTML tags/attributes except safe ones

Output encoding: contexts properly escaped

Then no generic payload will execute alert(1) unless you find:

A DOM sink where user input controls part of a dynamically created script (e.g., eval() with a partial injection)

A server‑side injection into JSON that later becomes JavaScript (e.g., {"name":"</script><script>alert(1)"})

CSS injection leading to script execution via expression() (only old IE)

Template injection in Angular, Vue, or React with dangerouslySetInnerHTML

The most exceptional modern payload that bypasses all filters is context‑dependent – e.g., inside a javascript: URL inside a data: URI that is then imported via <iframe srcdoc>. But a universal one does not exist. For a demo, I’d pick:

<svg><script>alert(1)</script> – because it uses mutation and is surprisingly effective even against some sanitizers.

But if you want the most evil one that works sometimes against otherwise safe code, try:

<math><mtext><table><mglyph><style><img src=x onerror=alert(1)>

This causes a parser re‑entrancy that executes onerror after sanitization.
